Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a law to protect union organizing as a civil right.
&quot;Depending on how the unions work, the jobs for the middle class work,&quot; said Ellison, a Minnesota Democratic senator who is co-chair of the Congressional Committee.
That&#39;s why I&#39;m so proud to be able to introduce an employee empowerment law with John Lewis, a model of occasional rights.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to combat discrimination in trade union organization as other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces.
It is a right and necessary initiative to amend the law on employment relations so that it allows all employees who face discrimination if they want to join a trade union to go to court in a civil court - and to assess compensation or damages.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents of the law put forward is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand and respect labor rights.
There were times, and millions of Americans still remember them, when the country promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble with one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toja&#39;s military autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Convinced that workers and their unions had a role to play in shaping the new Japan, they included language and openly acknowledged that &quot;the right of workers to assemble, bargain collectively and act collectively is guaranteed.&quot;
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler&#39;s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that employees would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that openly states: “The right to form associations that secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every occupation or profession.
Arrangements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will be terminated. Measures to achieve such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the drafters and Roosevelt included a guarantee that &quot;everyone has the right to protection create and join unions. &quot;
Americans for generations have adopted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to form labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that the unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but expanded it.
They have raised the living standards of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unsuspected level.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labor rights as human - and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination in the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that lifted America and made it a true promise of democracy.
