He had mesothelioma, an incurable tumor that affects the pleura or the lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it is difficult to determine what was causing them.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, not all lung cancer patients smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, it is the cause of exposure to asbestos - a building fibrous material that was previously described as &quot;miraculous&quot;, but is now known to be deadly.
It was not difficult for most of us to ignore mesothelioma.
Asbestos, after all, is a thing of the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in Britain since the 1960s, when a ban on the use of asbestos in industry came into force.
Even at the time when asbestos was used, only certain groups of people came into close contact with it, such as insulators, builders, carpenters and shipyard workers.
The toxin used in industry in another era hardly seems to be a cause for concern today.
But such complacency is out of place.
As it turns out, the mesothelioma epidemic is culminating in Britain today.
The number of mesothelioma deaths is higher here than in any other country in the world.
2,500 deaths from the disease per year are twice as many as the number of car accident victims.
