Why the universe can have more dimensions and we don&#39;t see them
Physicists usually don&#39;t write bestsellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University made a hit in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for laymen to penetrate the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists are working on today - trying to unite two well-functioning but incompatible 20th century discoveries: quantum theory and general relativity.
Undoubtedly, one of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the basic problem between two key theories (after all, at the moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and they are solving so imaginatively that it is worth retelling to lay people.
In addition, Greene handled the complex material so freshly and engagingly that he could not be blamed for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he largely corrected his &quot;mistake&quot; in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object if his book became obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a little more lively in this area (perhaps because the LHC accelerator will finally run at &quot;full throttle&quot;), so it is a good time to enter the non-violently open door of the world of modern physics.
How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may certainly sound foolish, fantastic, strange or mystical.
Nevertheless, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us turn our eyes for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden watering hose.
Imagine stretching a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the entire scenery from a half-kilometer distance (as in the picture and on the following page).
From such a distance, you can easily notice a long horizontally stretched hose, but if you do not suffer from foresight, you will hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Due to its large distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which it can walk: a left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at the time, you only answer with one indication: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a half-kilometer distance, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, a hose has a thickness.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see the second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can in fact move in two independent dimensions: in the well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the &quot;clockwise / counterclockwise dimension&quot;, i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You are beginning to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you must enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where the wrapping hose is on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note: Experts will notice that this chapter focuses purely on the failure theory of strings.
Non-fault aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is shown by a straight arrow, the dimension in the circumferential direction, indicated by a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between the two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easily visible.
The size of the wrapping circumference of the hose is short, &quot;coiled&quot; and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important property of spatial dimensions.
That they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, large, and therefore directly visible, or, conversely, small, coiled and much less observable.
Of course, in this case, we did not precede ourselves to reveal the &quot;coiled&quot; dimension wrapping around the thickness of the hose.
All you had to do was take the binoculars to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would only be able to detect the coiled dimension with great effort.
Kaluza sent his article to Einstein in 1919, in which he came up with the astonishing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to us all.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by saying that the additional dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein&#39;s general relativity and Maxwell&#39;s electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises as to how this Kaluz observation goes together with the obvious fact that we see exactly three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly stated and specified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls, arguing that the spatial geometry of our universe can be both large and coiled.
This means that, like the dimensions in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has three large, vast and easily visible dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of at all times.
But analogous to the circular circumference of a garden hose, the universe can also have additional dimensions, tightly wound into a space so small that they have remained hidden from our most perfect experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer idea of the nature of Kaluz&#39;s remarkable design, let&#39;s stay with the hose for a moment.
Imagine that we draw a relatively dense row of circles on the circumference of the hose in black.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With binoculars, thanks to the drawing, we can now reveal the coiled dimension even easier, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but in addition to one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, together a four-spatial dimension.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, let&#39;s take a look at the illustration in Fig.3; shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of the space in the same way as we enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are rolled into a sufficiently small space; this explains that we have not yet observed them directly.
The square grid represents the commonly known &quot;large&quot; dimensions, while the circle represents the new, tiny, and coiled dimensions.
Just like loops of thread in a densely woven carpet, these circles also exist in every place of the usual dimensions - we just drew them only at the intersections in a square network for the sake of clarity.
The background of Figure 4 shows the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - on such common scales as meters, represented by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each subsequent image, we will focus on a small area of the previous image; we enlarge it to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see at the first few levels of magnification.
However, as we move on to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space further - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, circularly wound dimension, similar to loops of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at each point in the direction of large dimensions, just as a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn the circular dimension only at some, regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluz&#39;s and Klein&#39;s idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also notice important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has only one large dimension.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object within the universe, such as our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly coiled dimension is extremely miniature, it is much more difficult to recognize it - like the circular circumference of the hose - than to observe the obvious, large and large dimensions.
If the size of the additional dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our state-of-the-art magnification tools.
Most importantly, however, the additional dimension is not just a round bump within the normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at each point of the three common large dimensions.
It is a dimension independent of the other three dimensions as well as top-down, left-right and front-back dimensions independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A small enough ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual positions in the circular dimension; if we also count the time, then the data are five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
