To our surprise, we find that although we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluz&#39;s and Klein&#39;s reasoning shows that this does not preclude the existence of additional coiled dimensions if they are small enough.
The universe can easily have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
State-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize structures as large as one billionth of a billionth of a meter.
We can hardly observe smaller coiled dimensions.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluz&#39;s original idea with several ideas from the nascent quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the additional circular dimension could be about one Planck length, far beyond the resolution of today&#39;s instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional small spatial dimensions the Kaluz-Klein theory.
