Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman from Britain describes how, after a misdiagnosis, she thought she would die for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence, thinking she had only a few years left to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth Syndrome (CMT) - a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
Approximately 23,000 people in the United Kingdom are estimated to suffer from CMT, which can include motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, clumsy gait and twisted toes.
Insensitivity or pain may also occur in those affected, which is incurable and progressive, meaning that the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich&#39;s ataxia (FA) - a disease with a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before she celebrated her eighteenth birthday, she would be confined to a wheelchair, and dead before she was thirty.
The mother of two, now 51, says: “As a child, I knew I couldn&#39;t do the same things as others.
I fell every day and everything took longer.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with other children, and I was bullied at school because of the way I walked and ran. ”
When Rodgers was thirteen and had several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor leaving the room and looked in her file to learn that she was suffering from FA.
&quot;I felt guilty because I was snooping, so I didn&#39;t tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,&quot; he says.
When they answered me, I was shocked, I panicked completely.
I thought that before I was eighteen, I would end up in a wheelchair, and before I was twenty-five, I would be dead, and in the meantime I would gradually lose all my abilities.
I was completely alone and I was planning a funeral. &quot;
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had expected, and she asked her surgeon.
He just stood up, hugged her and said, &quot;Honey, I don&#39;t think you have the disease, or you&#39;ll be in a wheelchair.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening. &quot;
After undergoing several genetic tests, he was found to have CMT.
&quot;When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a child of fortune,&quot; she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched a month of awareness about CMT to raise awareness of the disease.
Entrepreneurs in the Washington area: with the turn of the economy, taxes are rising
A growing economy means more customers, higher sales and new jobs.
And also higher taxes.
According to a new survey released last week, state and local corporate taxation in the country has accelerated slightly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, and companies in Washington were no exception.
Entrepreneurs in Maryland and Virginia together spent $ 27.6 billion in state and local coffers in fiscal 2013, 3.8% more than the $ 26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden - both state and local - rose 4.3% last year to $ 671 billion compared to 3.9% last year, the third year in a row after 2009 and 2010 when taxes were cut.
According to a study by the professional firm Ernst &amp; Young and the political group Center on State Taxation, state taxes increased faster, by 4.3%, than local levies, by 3.9%.
More than half of the county&#39;s tax revenue, 56%, is from trade tax, and 36% of Maryland&#39;s revenue is from companies.
Virginia, with 28%, has the proportionately small tax revenue from business.
Researchers claim that the majority share of tax revenue growth comes from an increase in the value of real estate belonging to companies, which increased real estate taxes by 3.7% this year after three consecutive years with growth of -1%.
Although most of the profits come from big states like California, New York and Texas, the situation seems to be the same in Washington.
Companies in DC, Maryland and Vrigini paid more than $ 10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, an annual increase of 4.2% from 2012 billion.
However, the apparent increase in property value does not drive up state and local tax revenues so much in Maryland, where property taxes account for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and DC, property tax accounts for nearly half of state and local taxation.
&quot;In Maryland, a lot of real estate companies own, especially the tax base around DC, the government or non-profit organizations that don&#39;t pay taxes,&quot; explained Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in business tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovering real estate market.
According to the data, it seems that business income is also increasing.
Businesses in the region have posted $ 2.3 billion in corporate income tax, up from $ 2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland has collected $ 1 billion in corporate income taxes, the most in the region.
Although they are moving in the same direction, the local tax burden on businesses is not growing as fast in these three places.
The growth rate in DC was at the national average, at 4.3%, while Maryland&#39;s growth was significantly higher at 4.9%.
In Virginia alone, tax increases were below average, to 4.1%.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax of all three districts (all of which have the same taxation), 6%.
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25%, while the DC average remains relatively high, at 9.975%.
A similar study conducted this year by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce found that Virginia has lower state and local taxation and an overall more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
DC did not evaluate the study.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces competitive pressure from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law reducing the corporate tax from 6.9% to 6%, as did Virginia, and next year the tax will be reduced to 5%.
If the state continues to meet its revenue targets in the coming year, the statutory income tax rate could be reduced to 3% in 2017.
According to a recent study, small businesses in Washington are doing better and therefore pay higher state and local taxes.
Trade tax levied by small businesses as a personal income tax - a cost-compensating structure by which most companies are organized - in DC, Maryland and Virginia rose 20% to $ 2.4 billion last year, much faster than other taxes.
The researchers say that the trend and nationwide increase in the trade tax are likely to continue next year, with total sales tax revenues for state and local governments increasing to 6.2% over the same period last year in the first three quarters of 2014.
However, Washington may lag behind others as government spending cuts take its toll on the labor market.
